      "front": "You need globally unique order IDs without a single database sequence. Compare random UUIDs with time-ordered IDs such as UUIDv7 or Snowflake-style IDs.",
      "back": "- **Random UUIDs**: generated anywhere with no coordination and hard to guess. Their random index insertion pattern can reduce B-tree locality, and they do not naturally sort by creation time.\n- **UUIDv7**: standardized, time-ordered UUIDs with random bits. They preserve decentralized generation while improving temporal locality; generation must handle clock behavior correctly.\n- **Snowflake-style IDs**: pack time, worker identity, and a per-time-unit sequence into an integer. They are compact and ordered, but require unique worker IDs and explicit behavior for clock rollback or sequence exhaustion.\n\nChoose from requirements: interoperability, index locality, opacity, size, ordering, and tolerance for coordination.",
      "explanation": "\u201cGlobally unique\u201d is only the start. Sequential public IDs leak volume and make enumeration easy. Time-ordered IDs improve locality but reveal approximate creation time. Random IDs avoid worker coordination but are wider and scatter inserts.\n\nDo not use an ID\u2019s timestamp as the authoritative business creation time. Store that separately so clock corrections and imports do not change product semantics.",
