      "front": "What is **cell-based architecture**, and what problem does it solve that ordinary horizontal scaling doesn't?",
      "back": "Partition the *entire stack* (compute + storage + dependencies) into N self-contained **cells**, each serving a fixed slice of customers, with a thin routing layer on top.\n\n- Ordinary scaling shares fate: one poison request, bad deploy, or overloaded dependency can take down **all** users.\n- Cells cap **blast radius**: an incident hits ~1/N of customers; the rest never notice.\n- Enables **canary-by-cell** deploys and per-cell capacity limits (a cell is never allowed to grow past tested size).",
      "explanation": "Cells are primarily an isolation tool. Choose a size that can be load-tested as a unit without creating excessive overhead. Customer-to-cell placement must be stable and migratable. Keep shared layers\u2014especially routing\u2014small and reliable, because any shared dependency can restore the global blast radius the cells were meant to remove. Shuffle sharding can further limit which tenants share a failure domain.",
