      "front": "A database recovers from a 20-second failover, but the service stays down for 45 minutes. Three layers each made up to three attempts per request. Explain the feedback loop.",
      "back": "**Chain**: failover \u2192 retries at each layer \u2192 up to 27 attempts per original request \u2192 recovered database saturates again \u2192 more timeouts and retries. The trigger ended, but the load loop remained: a metastable failure.\n\n**Principles**:\n1. **Retry budgets** and one designated retry layer.\n2. **Exponential backoff with jitter** \u2014 spread retries instead of synchronizing them.\n3. **Load shedding / admission control** at the recovering resource, so it can climb out.",
      "explanation": "This is a *metastable failure*: the trigger heals, but the feedback loop\u2014timeouts, retries, overload, more timeouts\u2014keeps the system outside its stable operating region. Retry policy must be designed across layers because attempts multiply. Recovery also needs spare capacity or deliberate shedding; otherwise the retry backlog can immediately consume every resource that returns.",
