      "reviewedBy": "M",
      "front": "Your page has a **200 ms p99 budget** and the render calls 5 services **sequentially**. Why is giving each service 40 ms wrong, and what's the right way to think about it?",
      "back": "- Sequential p99s don't add like averages: if each service hits its own p99 independently, the *page* blows its budget far more than 1% of the time \u2014 **tail latencies compound** (at 1% each, ~5% of pages see at least one slow call).\n- Right approach: budget for **p99 of the sum**, which means each dependency needs to be well under its share \u2014 or restructure:\n  1. **Parallelize** independent calls (budget = max, not sum).\n  2. **Hedge/retry** the slowest call after ~p95.\n  3. Cut the chain: fewer sequential hops is worth more than faster hops.",
      "explanation": "Fan-out magnifies tail risk: if 100 independent calls each have a 1% chance of being slow, at least one is slow about 63% of the time. Reduce serial hops, propagate the remaining deadline, cap fan-out, and consider carefully controlled hedged requests for idempotent reads. A downstream service should stop work when the caller's deadline has expired.",
