      "front": "You're sharding a multi-tenant SaaS database (10k businesses; the largest is 1000\u00d7 the median). Candidate shard keys: **tenant_id**, **user_id**, or **hash(row_id)**. Pick one and defend it.",
      "back": "**tenant_id, with an escape hatch \u2014 and say the escape hatch out loud.**\n\n- `tenant_id`: keeps each tenant's queries on one shard (no scatter-gather, per-tenant isolation & migration). Risk: the 1000\u00d7 tenant becomes a **jumbo shard**.\n- `user_id`: spreads load but shatters tenant-scoped queries (most queries in B2B SaaS) across every shard.\n- `hash(row_id)`: perfect balance, worst locality \u2014 every real query fans out.\n\nEscape hatch: shard by tenant, but allow **the few whale tenants to get dedicated shards** (or be internally partitioned). Directory-based routing (tenant \u2192 shard map) makes this possible; pure hash routing doesn't.",
      "explanation": "Balance and locality must be evaluated together. Hashing `row_id` spreads rows evenly but makes tenant queries touch every shard. A directory turns shard placement into a changeable routing decision, which allows a large tenant to move or split without changing every other tenant.",
