      "front": "What actually differs between a **relational (SQL)** database and the main **NoSQL** families?",
      "back": "- **Relational (Postgres, MySQL)**: tables + joins, strong schema, ACID transactions, rich ad-hoc queries.\n- **Key-value (DynamoDB, Redis)**: get/put by key; scales horizontally; you design for access patterns up front.\n- **Document (MongoDB)**: nested JSON per record; flexible schema; multi-document ACID transactions exist (4.0+) but cost enough that the idiom is still embedding related data in one document.\n- **Wide-column (Cassandra)**: write-optimized, partition-key access, tunable consistency.\n- Rule of thumb: **start relational**; move a workload out only when a concrete access pattern or scale need demands it.",
